sures. For people trained in psychology or sociology, the bias has been toward the former, using surveys and experiments that yield readily comparable numerical results. For people trained in anthropology, it has been toward the latter, using ethnographic observations and interviews that offer richer nuances of meaning but are difficult to compare across societies. Discussing their own endeavors to combine the quantitative with the qualitative, the authors invite readers into a conversation about the best designs and practices of mixed methodologies to stimulate creative ideas and find new pathways of insight. The result is an engaging exploration of a promising new approach to the social sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSocial sciencesxMethodology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asocial sciences methodology, popular psychology research, scientists, successful examples, mixed methods, researchers, qualitative measures, sociology, numerical results, anthropology, ethnographic observations, interviews, holistic, clinical care, trigger films, ecocultural theory, autism, child development, biological predispositions, ethnography, cultural values, early developmental delays, intervention, transgender sex workers, education.1 aBernheimer, Lucinda P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaley, Tamara C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiego Vigil, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Greg J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuligni, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallimore, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarkness, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab